===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} ''[[remembren#Middle English|remembren]]'' from {{etyl|fro}} ''[[remembrer#Old French|remembrer]]'' from {{etyl|LL.}} ''[[rememorari]]'' "to remember again" from ''[[re-]]'' + ''[[memor]]'' "mindful" from {{proto|Indo-European|(s)mer-|to think about, be mindful, remember|lang=}}. The success of the {{fro}} word was aided by its proximity in sound and meaning to an existing {{etyl|gem}} word: {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|mimorian|lang=ang}}, {{term|mymerian|lang=ang}} "to remember, commemorate" from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|mimor|lang=ang}} "mindful" from {{proto|Germanic|mīmr-, maimr-, mimr-|to remember, be mindful|lang=}}, from the same {{proto|Indo-European}} source. Akin to {{etyl|frs|-}} ''[[mimerje|mīmerje]]'' "to ponder, reflect", {{etyl|gml|-}} ''[[mimeren|mīmeren, mīmern]]'' "to ponder, meditate", {{etyl|dum|-}} ''[[mimeren#Middle Dutch|mīmeren]]'' "to reflect, think to oneself" ({{etyl|nld|-}} ''[[mijmeren]]'' "to muse, reflect deeply"), {{etyl|non|-}} ''[[Mímir]]'', ''[[Mim]]'', Norse god of Memory and Wisdom, {{ang}} ''[[mamrian#Old English|māmrian]]'' "to think out, design". Displaced native {{enm}} ''''[[ȝemuneȝen#Middle English|ȝemuneȝen]]'' "to remember" (from {{ang}} ''[[gemynegian#Old English|ġemynegian]]'' "to remember, remind"), {{enm}} ''[[minnen#Middle English|minnen]]'' "to remember, have in mind" (from {{non}} ''[[minna#Old Norse|minna]]'' "to remind"), {{enm}} ''[[ȝemunden#Middle English|munden, ȝemunden]]'' "to bear in mind, remember" (from {{ang}} ''[[gemynd#Old English|ġemynd]]'' "memory, remembrance"), {{enm}} ''[[ȝethenchen#Middle English|ȝethenchen, ithenchen]]'' "to think on, remember" (from {{ang}} ''[[geþencan#Old English|ġeþencan]]''), {{enm}} ''[[manien#Middle English|manien]]'' "to remind, mention, remember" (from {{ang}} ''[[manian#Old English|manian]]'' "to admonish, remind, mention").

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# To [[recall]] from one's [[memory]]; to have an image in one's memory.
#: ''I '''remember''' the formula.''
#: ''I '''remember''' locking the door.''
#* {{quote-book|1852|Mrs M.A. Thompson|chapter=The Tutor's Daughter|Graham's American Monthly Magazine of Literature, Art, and Fashion|page=266|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=hdcRAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA266
|passage=In the lightness of my heart I sang catches of songs as my horse gayly bore me along the well-'''remembered''' road.}}
# To [[memorize]]; to put something into memory.
#: ''Please '''remember''' this formula!''
# To not forget (to do something required)
#: '''''Remember''' to lock the door when you go out.''
# To [[convey]] greetings.
#: ''Please '''remember''' me to your brother.''
# {{obsolete}} To [[put in mind]]; to [[remind]] (also used reflexively)
#* [[:w:Dante Gabriel Rossetti|Dante Gabriel Rossetti]], Secret Parting, lines 5-7
#*: ''But soon, '''remembering her''' how brief the whole
#*: ''Of joy, which its own hours annihilate,
#*: ''Her set gaze gathered
# {{intransitive}} To engage in the process of recalling memories.
#: ''You don't have to remind him, he '''remembers''' very well.''

====Usage notes====
* In sense 1 this is a [[catenative]] verb that takes the ''gerund (-ing)''.
* In sense 3 this is a [[catenative]] verb that takes the ''to'' infinitive.
